<bibRefCitation author="Pinheiro" box="[692,978,367,392]" pageId="10" pageNumber="256" refString="Pinheiro, L. R. &amp; Duarte, M. (2016) Description of nine new species of Heliura Butler from South America (Lepidoptera, Erebidae, Arctiinae, Arctiini, Ctenuchina). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, 51 (3 - 4), 310 - 330." type="journal article" year="2016">Pinheiro &amp; Duarte, 2016</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Even though 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duarte" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Zerny" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[1145,1296,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Heliura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="256" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fenestrifer" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1145,1296,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="256">H. fenestrifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1305,1436,367,392]" pageId="10" pageNumber="256">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1305,1436,367,392]" pageId="10" pageNumber="256">comb. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
does not have acute angles in the hindwings as in the other species in the group, they all share a highly peculiar hindwing venation (fig. 6), plus several characters of male genitalia, such as a long and thin saccus, and subdivided valvae with a dorsal highly sclerotized portion, and a ventral, slightly sclerotized portion.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,151,645]" pageId="10" pageNumber="256">
As in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schaus" authorityYear="1894" box="[265,337,513,536]" class="Insecta" family="Cercopidae" genus="Ptychotrichos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="256" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zeus">
<emphasis box="[265,337,513,536]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="256">P. zeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the wide distribution of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duarte" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Zerny" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[621,769,512,536]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Heliura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="256" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fenestrifer" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[621,769,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="256">H. fenestrifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[776,904,511,536]" pageId="10" pageNumber="256">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[776,904,511,536]" pageId="10" pageNumber="256">comb. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
raises doubt that a single taxon has such a wide distribution. However, the rarity of specimens of this group in collections and the lack of possibility to barcode old museum specimens have prevented the examination of the number of taxa involved in what we are here calling 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duarte" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Zerny" baseAuthorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Heliura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="256" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fenestrifer" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="256">H. fenestrifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[273,401,620,645]" pageId="10" pageNumber="256">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[273,401,620,645]" pageId="10" pageNumber="256">comb. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
